<subSubSection lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="2116" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="19.[160,1155,679,773]" box="[160,276,679,704]" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,276,679,704]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="19.[160,1155,679,773]" lastBlockId="20.[160,1156,142,305]" lastPageId="20" lastPageNumber="2116" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115">
This species strongly resembles 
<taxonomicName authority="Li, Gao and Chen, 2010" authorityName="Li, Gao and Chen" authorityYear="2010" box="[519,899,713,738]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Pseudostegana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insularis">
<emphasis box="[519,634,713,738]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115">P. insularis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Li T &amp; Gao JJ &amp; Chen HW" box="[641,899,714,738]" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115" pagination="1401 - 1418" refId="ref9015" refString="Li T, Gao JJ, Chen HW. 2010. Six new species of the genus Pseudostegana (Diptera: Drosophilidae) from the Oriental Region. J Nat Hist. 44: 1401 - 1418." type="journal article" year="2010">Li, Gao and Chen, 2010</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[966,1048,714,738]" country="China" name="Hainan" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115">Hainan</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry box="[1058,1125,714,738]" name="China" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115">China</collectingCountry>
, in the body colour (
<figureCitation box="[353,447,749,773]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="10.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 5. Head, thorax, wing and abdomen of male: (a–f) Pseudostegana montipagana sp. nov.; (g–l) P. sigangli sp. nov." pageId="19" pageNumber="2115">Figure 5</figureCitation>
(a–f)) and male terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[748,857,749,773]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="19.[160,225,823,846]" captionText="Figure 11. Pseudostegana montipagana sp. nov., male terminalia. (a) epandrium, cercus and surstylus; (b, c) hypandrium, paramere, gonopods, aedeagus and aedeagal apodeme (ventral and lateral views). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." pageId="19" pageNumber="2115">Figure 11</figureCitation>
), but can be distinguished from it by the wing pattern and aedeagus; in this species, medial band of wing medially broadened (
<figureCitation box="[296,389,177,201]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="10.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 5. Head, thorax, wing and abdomen of male: (a–f) Pseudostegana montipagana sp. nov.; (g–l) P. sigangli sp. nov." pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">Figure 5</figureCitation>
(c)); aedeagus basally strong, and subapically slightly curved ventrad in lateral view (
<figureCitation box="[333,439,212,236]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="19.[160,225,823,846]" captionText="Figure 11. Pseudostegana montipagana sp. nov., male terminalia. (a) epandrium, cercus and surstylus; (b, c) hypandrium, paramere, gonopods, aedeagus and aedeagal apodeme (ventral and lateral views). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">Figure 11</figureCitation>
(c)). The 8.9% interspecific genetic distance to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Li, Gao and Chen" authorityYear="2010" box="[969,1085,211,236]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Pseudostegana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="2116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insularis">
<emphasis box="[969,1085,211,236]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">P. insularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the smallest within this group; there are seven diagnostic sites between 
<taxonomicName authority="Gong &amp; Chen, 2018" authorityName="Gong &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2018" box="[940,1116,245,270]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Pseudostegana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="2116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montipagana" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[940,1116,245,270]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">P. montipagana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="20" pageNumber="2116" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Li, Gao and Chen" authorityYear="2010" box="[268,385,280,305]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Pseudostegana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="20" pageNumber="2116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insularis">
<emphasis box="[268,385,280,305]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">P. insularis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[400,497,281,305]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="7.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 2. Diagnostic nucleotide sites in the alignment of the COI sequences of the genus Pseudostegana. Numbers at the top show the positions of the sites in the COI alignment (656–684 bp in length). Shaded sites are diagnostic for each species. Dashes (−) indicate missing data." pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">Figure 2</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption pageId="19" pageNumber="2115" startId="19.[160,225,823,846]">
<paragraph blockId="19.[160,1159,822,905]" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,265,823,846]" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115">Figure 11.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Gong &amp; Chen, 2018" authorityName="Gong &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2018" box="[273,555,822,845]" class="Insecta" family="Drosophilidae" genus="Pseudostegana" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="montipagana" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[273,555,822,845]" italics="true" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115">Pseudostegana montipagana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[563,644,823,846]" pageId="19" pageNumber="2115" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, male terminalia. (a) epandrium, cercus and surstylus; (b, c) hypandrium, paramere, gonopods, aedeagus and aedeagal apodeme (ventral and lateral views). Scale bars: 0.1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="2116" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1156,349,859]" box="[160,294,349,374]" pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,294,349,374]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">Description</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1156,349,859]" pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,224,384,409]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">Male.</emphasis>
Head (
<figureCitation box="[313,409,385,409]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="10.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 5. Head, thorax, wing and abdomen of male: (a–f) Pseudostegana montipagana sp. nov.; (g–l) P. sigangli sp. nov." pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">Figure 5</figureCitation>
(a,d)): Ocellar triangle brown, nearly equally elongated to anterior margin of frons. Frons brown. Pedicel brownish; first flagellomere greyish yellow. Face brown above, dark brown below. Clypeus dark brown. Gena brown. Palpus greyish yellow, broad, large in male, medially half as wide as long. Thorax (
<figureCitation box="[993,1094,489,513]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="10.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 5. Head, thorax, wing and abdomen of male: (a–f) Pseudostegana montipagana sp. nov.; (g–l) P. sigangli sp. nov." pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">Figure 5</figureCitation>
(b,e)): Scutum brown and with one thin, dark medial stripe on anterior two-thirds, dark brown on posterior one-third. Pleura nearly dark brown. Katepisternal setae two. Scutellum dark brown. Legs: Yellow, dark brown on distal half of femora and tibiae of mid and hind legs. Abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[520,618,627,651]" captionStart="Figure 5" captionStartId="10.[160,225,121,144]" captionText="Figure 5. Head, thorax, wing and abdomen of male: (a–f) Pseudostegana montipagana sp. nov.; (g–l) P. sigangli sp. nov." pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">Figure 5</figureCitation>
(f)): First to third tergites dark brown, the rest black. Sternites yellowish brown on second and third, dark brown on the rest. Male terminalia (
<figureCitation box="[289,402,697,721]" captionStart="Figure 11" captionStartId="19.[160,225,823,846]" captionText="Figure 11. Pseudostegana montipagana sp. nov., male terminalia. (a) epandrium, cercus and surstylus; (b, c) hypandrium, paramere, gonopods, aedeagus and aedeagal apodeme (ventral and lateral views). Scale bars: 0.1 mm." pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">Figure 11</figureCitation>
): Epandrium slightly roundly protruding on ventral margin, with about 17 setae per side. Surstylus protruding on posteroventral corner. Cercus ventrally slightly elongated. Paramere apically slightly bifurcated, subapically with two long sensilla and several sensilla on dorsal projection. Basal process of aedeagus slender, distally with about five finger-like projections.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[160,1156,904,1067]" box="[160,333,904,929]" pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,333,904,929]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="2116">Measurements</emphasis>
